Layer-by-Layer Breakdown
1. The API Layer (api/)
main.py:  It's the standard FastAPI app factory where I mounted the router.

store.py: Simple in-memory dict keyed by run_id. Job store that is lightweight.

routes/pipeline.py: Holds my two main endpoints. POST /run triggers the job, and GET /status/{run_id} lets you check on it.

Why use BackgroundTasks?
The LLM calls mean a full pipeline run can easily take 30 to 120 seconds. I return an immediate response so the frontend isn't hanging, and the client can just poll the status endpoint.

Why an in-memory store?
This is meant to be a localized intelligence tool, not a massive distributed web service. I handle persistence simply by writing the final output files straight to data/outputs/.

2. Orchestration (pipeline/edges/routing.py)
I handle the flow using LangGraph's StateGraph. It’s essentially a directed graph where every node is just a pure function that takes in the state, modifies it, and passes it along.

Why LangGraph?

My pipeline is basically a DAG with specific early-exit points. LangGraph’s conditional edges make it really easy to bail out cleanly. For example, if the classifier doesn't find any SH-7 forms, the graph just stops right there instead of running empty downstream nodes and crashing.

State is managed via a single TypedDict (PipelineState) that gets passed around immutably, which makes debugging and replaying failed runs way less painful.

I explicitly ripped out the human-in-the-loop components to force deterministic, automated flagging. LangGraph's routing makes that determinism easy to map out.

3. Shared State (schemas/pipeline_state.py)
The PipelineState object carries about 17 fields that slowly build up as the graph executes. The flow looks like this:

run_id & input_folder
→ raw_files
→ classified_docs (split into SH-7s and non-SH-7s)
→ document_groups
→ attachment_bundles
→ extracted_sh7s
→ validation_reports
→ capital_table_rows
→ final_table_rows & discrepancy_report

Every time a node finishes, it tacks its name onto completed_stages and dumps any structured errors into pipeline_errors. I try to never raise actual Python exceptions unless a failure is totally unrecoverable.

4. The Pipeline Nodes (pipeline/nodes/)
Step 1: Ingestion (ingestion.py)
Grabs all the .md files from the target folder and spins up FileMetadata objects. There's zero LLM usage here. If a file fails to read, I log the error and just skip it—one bad file shouldn't tank the whole run.

Step 2: Classifier (classifier.py)
I use a two-pass classification system to save time and money.

Pass 1 (Rule-based): Checks filename and content keywords. Very fast, and covers well-named filings with high confidence (0.87 to 0.92).

Pass 2 (LLM Fallback): I fire up Ollama/Qwen via an OpenAI-compatible API only if the rule confidence dips below 0.85.

Anything scoring under 0.60 gets dumped into unclassified_documents. I also run a quick deduplication pass on SH-7s here if they share an event_date_hint.

Step 3: Relationship Resolver (relationship_resolver.py)
This node bundles the documents into DocumentGroup objects. It links every SH-7 to its matching Board Resolution, EGM Resolution, and MOA using filename patterns and date clues. I need this because SH-7s reference their attachments by name, so the next node needs to know exactly which files belong to which form.

Step 4: Attachment Extractor (attachment_extractor.py)
Takes each document group and extracts the exact structured data I need from the resolutions and MOA using LLM function calling. The output is an AttachmentExtractionBundle for each SH-7, strictly typed via Pydantic.

Step 5: SH-7 Extractor (sh7_extractor.py)
The heavy hitter of the pipeline. It pulls the full SH7Extraction from each form—grabbing the CIN, meeting date, old/new capital, Section 9(a) breakdown, SRN, and stamp duty. I wired up a Pydantic model_validator to cross-check the Section 9(a) math against Field 4(a)(i) in real-time. This catches parsing hallucinations instantly.

Step 6: Validator (validator.py)
This is where the complex logic lives. It runs four hard-coded checks:

Arithmetic: Just making sure existing + added actually equals revised. It won't block the run, just flags it.

Continuity: Strict block. If Event 2's starting capital doesn't match Event 1's final capital, I halt that branch.

Cross-doc: Checks if the SH-7 dates and numbers match the attached resolutions. One mismatch is a warning; all of them mismatching is a hard block.

Duplicate: If I see two SH-7s for the exact same meeting date, I block both to be safe.

Step 7: Assembler (assembler.py)
Constructs CapitalTableRow objects out of whatever SH-7s survived validation. Row 0 is just a fake "On Incorporation" row derived from the first event's starting capital. Every piece of data is stored as a FieldValue holding the value, the source document, and exactly where it came from, making the final table 100% traceable.

Step 8: Narrative Generator (narrative_generator.py)
Pretties up the dates for the frontend, compiles the final DiscrepancyReport, and writes three files to data/outputs/: the JSON capital table, the JSON discrepancy report, and a Jinja2-rendered HTML table.

5. Schemas (schemas/)
I went all-in on Pydantic V2 for this. Type safety is non-negotiable for financial data.

document.py: Manages metadata and grouping.

sh7.py / attachment.py: The extraction targets.

validation.py: Holds the check results.

capital_event.py / output.py: The final data models.

Using Pydantic gives me free JSON serialization, and the built-in validation errors actually tell you exactly which field blew up.

6. Services (services/)
llm_client.py: Wraps Ollama. It grabs Google GenAI tool definitions and mangles them into OpenAI's format to force structured JSON output out of the local model (qwen3-coder-next:cloud).

document_parser.py: Handles markdown reading and Indian currency formatting.

template_engine.py: Runs the Jinja renders.

Why Ollama instead of a cloud API? Local inference means zero network lag, zero API bills, and it works perfectly for offline compliance environments. If I ever need to swap to Gemini or OpenAI, the classifier has an environment variable ready to go.

7. Centralized Logging (logging_config.py)
Everything goes to the terminal and a rotating log file simultaneously through a single configure_logging() setup.

What the logs look like:
2026-05-24 07:36:43 | INFO  | root | Logging initialised | file=...pipeline_2026-05-24.log
2026-05-24 07:36:43 | INFO  | ...nodes.ingestion | Ingestion complete | files_read=20 errors=0
2026-05-24 07:36:43 | INFO  | ...nodes.relationship_resolver | DocumentGroup built | sh7=SH7_Event1.md event_index=1

I initialize this at the module level in the CLI script, and inside the FastAPI lifespan context manager for the API. It attaches a StreamHandler (for stdout) and a TimedRotatingFileHandler to the root logger. Because every node just calls logging.getLogger(__name__), the child loggers propagate up automatically. I didn't have to touch the logging code inside the individual nodes at all.


Why I Designed It This Way
Linear DAG, zero parallelism: I wanted it highly deterministic and easy to debug. Each stage's output is just the next stage's input.

Rule-based classifier first: Keeps expensive LLM calls to an absolute minimum.

FieldValue traceability: Any number you see on the final frontend table can be traced back to the exact field in the exact raw file.

No human intervention: Unresolvable ambiguities are explicitly flagged in the final report, not paused for manual review. It runs completely hands-off.
